Linux kernel
============
# Kali NetHunter Kernel for CD12M (xintaiqi_uws6152_1h10)

Custom kernel for the **CD12M** device (based on `xintaiqi_uws6152_1h10` platform) with full Kali NetHunter support.

## Features

- Built from official Android kernel source with NetHunter patches
- Wireless external adapter support (RTL88xx, MT76xx, Atheros AR9271, etc.)
- HID keyboard / mouse attack support
- USB gadget support (RNDIS, ECM, HID)
- DriveDroid / CDROM emulation
- SELinux permissive (optional)
- Additional TCP congestion algorithms
- Loadable module support for NetHunter chroot

## Device Info

- **Codename:** CD12M
- **Base kernel:** `xintaiqi_uws6152_1h10_test`
- **Defconfig:** `cd12m_defconfig` (or your custom defconfig)

## Build Instructions

### Prerequisites

- Linux build environment (Ubuntu / Kali recommended)
- `build-essential`, `bc`, `bison`, `flex`, `libssl-dev`, `git`, `device-tree-compiler`
- Cross-compiler toolchain (e.g., `aarch64-linux-gnu-` or `arm-linux-gnueabi-` depending on arch)

### Compilation Steps

```bash
# Clone the kernel source
git clone https://github.com/kaliroko/kernel_kali-nethunter_cd12m.git
cd kernel_kali-nethunter_cd12m

# Set environment variables
export ARCH=arm64                               # or arm
export CROSS_COMPILE=aarch64-linux-gnu-         # adjust for your toolchain
export PATH=/path/to/toolchain/bin:$PATH

# Clean and prepare config
make clean
make mrproper
make cd12m_defconfig    # or your actual defconfig

# Build the kernel
make -j$(nproc)
This file was moved to Documentation/admin-guide/README.rst

Please notice that there are several guides for kernel developers and users.
These guides can be rendered in a number of formats, like HTML and PDF.

In order to build the documentation, use ``make htmldocs`` or
``make pdfdocs``.

There are various text files in the Documentation/ subdirectory,
several of them using the Restructured Text markup notation.
See Documentation/00-INDEX for a list of what is contained in each file.

Please read the Documentation/process/changes.rst file, as it contains the
requirements for building and running the kernel, and information about
the problems which may result by upgrading your kernel.

